Alternatively, after sorting in ascending order, reverse the array. So in the Java code, after sorting, the elements are accessed in reverse order (from largest to smallest). So for Fortran, after sorting in ascending order, reverse the array so that c(1) is the largest element, c(2) next largest, etc. Then, during the loop, when i runs from 2 to n+1 (wait, no: in Java, the loop runs for i from 2 to n+1, which is a total of (n+1 -2 +1) =n steps. So the number of elements is n. So in Fortran, perhaps the loop runs from i=1 to n. Wait, in the Java code, the loop is:

for (int i=2; i <=n+1; i++) {
    val = a * i % mod;
    val *= c[n+1 -i];
    ...
} So when i ranges from 2 to n+1, n+1 -i ranges from (n+1 -2) =n-1 to 0. So for n elements. So in Fortran, after reversing the array, the elements are in descending order.

Let's reimplement the Java power function in Fortran. The Java function is:

static long power(long x, long n) {
    if (n ==0) return 1;
    mod = 1e9+7;
    val = power(x, n/2);
    val = val * val % mod;
    if (n%2 ==1) val = val * x % mod;
    return val;
} So in Fortran, we can implement this as a recursive function, but recursion in Fortran can be a bit tricky.
